04050nam a22006135i 9789815104820DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898151048207 a10.1355/97898151048202doi  a(DE-B1597)677637  a(OCoLC)1409683193  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0370002bisacsh1 aPermono, Prakoso, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTerrorism in Indonesia and the Perceived Oppression of Muslims Worldwide /cPrakoso Permono, A'an Suryana. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (32 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tTerrorism in Indonesia and the Perceived Oppression of Muslims Worldwide -- tINTRODUCTION -- tMUSLIM SOLIDARITY MOTIVATION AND METHODOLOGY -- tTHE WORLDVIEW OF JIHADISTS: UMMAH AND MUSLIM SOLIDARITY -- tMUSLIM SOLIDARITY, PERCEIVED OPPRESSION OF MUSLIMS AND VIOLENT JIHAD -- tPERCEIVED MUSLIM OPPRESSION IN INDIA, CHINA AND MYANMAR -- tTHE GOVERNMENT’S ROLE -- tCONCLUSION -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVarious motivations underlying terrorism uncovered by recent scholarship include the radicals’ desire for Muslim unity, political interest, yearning to correct social and economic deprivation in the Muslim world, and simply anti-Westernism. This article focuses on the radicals’ call for Muslim solidarity and how this tends towards becoming their primary motivation for perpetrating terrorism. It discusses how radical groups and individuals exaggerate the perceived oppression of Muslims worldwide and how this encourages their sympathizers in planning, fundraising and/or executing terrorist attacks. The so-called ummah solidarity discourse is coupled with the prevalence of the dogma that Muslims are targets of Western or foreign oppression. This has legitimized jihadist terrorists’ use of violence and facilitated the recruitment of new terrorists. Besides regular crackdowns on terrorists and putting limitations on access to radical websites and other Internet sources, this article contends that the Indonesian security apparatuses and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs must work with the embassies from India, China and Myanmar based in Jakarta to nullify any likelihood of terror attacks on their embassy compounds or their citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh1 aPermono, Prakoso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuryana, A'an, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSuryana, A’an, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981510482040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815104820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815104820/original  a978-3-11-117804-2  DG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2b2023  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles